File: platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands/extension-commands.ts (handleBrowserExecuteScript, lines 352-475)

The bug: handleBrowserExecuteScript uses Promise.race between an async IIFE (injectPromise, lines 369-456) and a timeout promise (lines 458-462). When the timeout wins, the error response is sent (line 472-473), but the IIFE keeps running in the background — it has no way to know the race was lost. The IIFE continues calling chrome.scripting.executeScript to poll for results, and eventually runs a cleanup script that deletes __lastExecResult and __lastExecAsync from the page's __openTabs global. If a NEW browser.executeScript call starts before the stale IIFE finishes, the stale cleanup can delete the new call's globals, producing incorrect results.

Fix approach: Create a simple cancellation mechanism using a mutable object in the closure:

```typescript
const cancelled = { value: false };
```

Pass this into the IIFE and check `cancelled.value` at the top of the while loop (line 382). In the finally block after Promise.race (line 467), set `cancelled.value = true`.

Also skip the cleanup script (lines 441-453) if cancelled — the outer timeout already sent the error, and running cleanup later would race with subsequent executions.

The pattern is:
```typescript
const cancelled = { value: false };
const injectPromise = (async () => {
  // ... initial injection ...
  while (elapsed <= EXEC_MAX_ASYNC_WAIT_MS) {
    if (cancelled.value) return { value: { error: 'Cancelled by outer timeout' } };
    // ... existing polling logic ...
  }
  // Only clean up if not cancelled
  if (!cancelled.value) {
    await chrome.scripting.executeScript({ ... cleanup ... }).catch(() => {});
  }
  return { value: { error: `Async code did not resolve within ${EXEC_MAX_ASYNC_WAIT_MS}ms` } };
})();

// ... timeoutPromise ...

try {
  result = await Promise.race([injectPromise, timeoutPromise]);
} finally {
  clearTimeout(timeoutId);
  cancelled.value = true;
}
```
